    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.5-7_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">5</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        411 West 115 St. <hi rend="caps">N.Y.C</hi>
                        May 17. 1930
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John Neihardt,</salute>
                    <note type="curatorial">[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]</note>
                </opener>
                <p><hi rend="underline">Do let me have a line from you.</hi> You have become such a great factor in my life, that your silence troubles me: <hi rend="underline">please break it</hi>.</p>
                
                <p>A few weeks ago Dr. House came to see me. I enjoyed him immensely &#8212; and am deeply
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.5-7_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                    grateful for the showing he gave me in his magazine.</p>
                
                <p>I sent you one of the first copies of the <hi rend="underline">Leonardo</hi>. I am not surrounded by <hi rend="underline">Indians</hi>: fourteen sonnets of the sequence have gone through: <unclear>Tadousac</unclear>, Jacques Cartier, Vincent de Paul, No&#235;l Brulart de Sillery, Jean de Brebeux, Marie de l'Tucamutiou, <add>Port Royal</add>, Paul le Jeune, <del>Isaac</del> The Forest Peace (Champlain), Isaac Joques, Joques at the Court, Lac du Saint Sacrement, Inonatiria (the Huron Indian Village), The Mission of Sainte 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.5-7_0003"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                    
                    Marie. I hope for about four more to make the sequence complete.</p>
                
                <p><hi rend="underline">The Mission of Sainte Marie</hi> (on <unclear>Labettuou</unclear>), was written on May Eve. <hi rend="underline">The next morning</hi> I received from <hi rend="underline">the <unclear>Sault</unclear> Sainte Marie</hi> a box of <unclear/>, and <hi rend="underline">from Auriesvilla</hi> (in the Mowhawk Valley <add>where Joques was martyred</add>) a little piece of silk "from National <unclear>wrapped</unclear> about the relics of Jean <unclear>Brebeaux</unclear>, Gabriel Lalemont, and <unclear>Charles</unclear> Garnier"! The sonnet fortells the martyrdom of these three. &#8212; God and his Saints bless you ever.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Affectionately,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Thomas S. Jones Jr.</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
